e for someone who lived by a meadow, from Middle English <i>mede</i> ‘meadow’ (Old English <i>mǣd</i>), or a habitational name from one or more of the many places so named, such as Meads in Harford (Devon).","perhaps from Middle English <i>mede</i> ‘mead, alcoholic drink of fermented honey and water’, possibly denoting one who was fond of the drink or who made or sold mead. Compare   Meader  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":47,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Meade was born in 1502, in Clavering, Essex, England, his father, Sir Robert Mede, was 22 and his mother, Lady Joan de Somerset, was 24. He had at least 1 son with Joan Wycliffe. He died in 1557, in Great Easton, Essex, England, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1502–1557":"1502–1557","1498–1557":"1498–1557","1515–1559":"1515–1559","1480–1535":"1480–1535","1478–1548":"1478–1548","1502":"1502","1535":"1535","1557":"1